Great catch.  This is definitely a bug, but this fix will break other stuff.  The bug is that in the `rowUpdater.getNumRows() > config.getMaxIntermediateRows()` case (i.e. we have generated more rows than we need), we need to advance the cursor, which is currently not happening and will cause the row to be processed twice.

However, in the `unprocessedKeys` case, that means that we didn't have enough memory to actually store all of the keys and actually do need to reprocess the row.  The reprocessing is done in the `if` block before the while loop and is safe to not have the cursor advanced.  So, the fix should really be to separate out the `if` into two checks

```
if (unprocessedKeys != null) {
  break;
}

cursor.advance();
if(rowUpdater.getNumRows() > config.getMaxIntermediateRows()) {
  break
}
```

Which means that the last chunk can probably just be put into the while condition:

```
while (!cursor.isDone() &&  rowUpdater.getNumRows() < config.getMaxIntermediateRows()) {
  ByteBuffer key = ByteBuffer.allocate(dimensions.size() * Ints.BYTES);

  unprocessedKeys = rowUpdater.updateValues(key, dimensions);
  if (unprocessedKeys != null) {
    break;
  }

  cursor.advance();
}
```

That said, we should definitely have some unit tests for this!
